# AWS IAM Least Privilege

## What I did:

- Created IAM user with over-permission (AdministratorAccess)
- Tested full access across AWS services
- Identified security risk of excessive permissions
- Removed AdministratorAccess policy
- Created custom least privilege policy
- Attached restricted policy to user
- Tested allowed and denied actions



## Key Learnings:

- Least privilege means giving only required permissions
- Over-permission is a major security risk
- AdministratorAccess should not be used unnecessarily
- Custom policies help enforce security boundaries
- Explicit deny overrides allow
- AWS follows default deny model



## Hands-on Summary:

- Initially attached `AdministratorAccess`
- Verified:
  - Full access to AWS services ❌ (security risk)
- Replaced with custom S3 read-only policy
- Verified:
  - Can view S3 buckets ✅
  - Cannot upload/delete objects ❌
- Successfully enforced least privilege
- Make new policies where uploading file and viewing file is permitted but now deleting or modifying it works



## Mistakes to Avoid:

- Granting full admin access to users
- Not reviewing permissions after attaching policies
- Ignoring least privilege principle
- Using wildcard (*) permissions carelessly



## Security Insight:

- Over-permission can lead to:
  - Data breaches
  - Resource deletion
  - Privilege escalation attacks
- Always restrict access based on actual need


